{"id": "2026-07-20-sports-spain-are-world-champions-torres-extra-time-stri", "date": "2026-07-20", "stream": "sports", "headline": "Spain are world champions — Torres' extra-time strike beats Argentina 1-0", "summary": "Ferran Torres' extra-time goal gave Spain a 1-0 win over defending champions Argentina in the 2026 World Cup final, Spain's second title and a European-plus-world double.", "url": "https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/49403084/2026-world-cup-final-spain-argentina-score-ferran-torres", "source_domain": "espn.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["via snippet"], "topics": ["sports"], "importance": 3, "display_body": "Ferran Torres, on as a substitute, drove home early in extra time (around the 106th minute) to give Spain a 1-0 win over Argentina in the World Cup final at MetLife Stadium outside New York on Sunday. It is Spain's second world title after 2010, and it completes a rare double: they were already European champions, so one nation now holds both trophies at once. The result crowns a young Spanish side built around Lamine Yamal and Nico Williams as the dominant force in the men's game — and it closes the book on Argentina's title defence, and on the 39-year-old Lionel Messi's bid to leave with the trophy in hand. The holders were reduced to ten men (Enzo Fernandez sent off) and managed only two shots across 120 minutes; Spain conceded just one goal in the whole tournament, the meanest defence of any World Cup winner, over a record eight matches in the new 48-team format co-hosted by the USA, Canada and Mexico. Torres became only the second substitute ever to score a World Cup final winner.", "why": "This is the sport's biggest prize, and it settles the argument over who the team of the era is — not Argentina, France or Brazil, but a Spain side young enough to stay there. For a casual viewer, it's the tournament that will frame the next four years of football.", "thread_id": "2026-07-20-sports-spain-are-world-champions-torres-extra-time-stri", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-20", "event_date": "2026-07-19", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Spain", "Argentina", "Ferran Torres", "FIFA World Cup", "Lionel Messi"]}
{"id": "2026-07-20-sports-switzerland-s-berset-tells-fifa-to-fix-the-game", "date": "2026-07-20", "stream": "sports", "headline": "Switzerland's Berset tells FIFA to fix the game's integrity before 2030", "summary": "Council of Europe chief Alain Berset demanded FIFA build an integrity framework before 2030, citing a red card he attributed to a Trump phone call, racist abuse and betting expansion.", "url": "https://www.srf.ch/news/international/geld-einfluss-rassismus-scharfe-kritik-von-alain-berset-an-der-fifa-reform-gefordert", "source_domain": "srf.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["single-source"], "topics": ["sports"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "As the final whistle blew, Alain Berset — the former Swiss federal councillor now Secretary General of the Council of Europe (the 46-nation human-rights body based in Strasbourg, separate from the EU) — publicly pressed FIFA to open an \"integrity\" dialogue that same evening and to build a framework before the 2030 World Cup. His central example, per SRF's reporting: a red card against US forward Folarin Balogun that was rescinded, which Berset attributed to a phone call from President Donald Trump — political influence, he argued, reaching onto the pitch itself. He also flagged racist abuse of players and FIFA's expansion into stadium betting partnerships as openings for fraud. The framing here — 'integrity', and the causal link between Trump's call and the reversal — is Berset's and SRF's characterisation; FIFA has not formally responded, and the causation claim rests on a single source.", "why": "When a European human-rights institution publicly asks whether a head of state swayed a match decision, the story stops being about the scoreline and becomes about who actually controls the game heading into the next tournament.", "thread_id": "2026-07-20-sports-switzerland-s-berset-tells-fifa-to-fix-the-game", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-20", "event_date": "2026-07-19", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Alain Berset", "Council of Europe", "FIFA", "Donald Trump", "Folarin Balogun"]}
{"id": "2026-07-20-sports-antonelli-wins-at-spa-and-opens-a-commanding-45", "date": "2026-07-20", "stream": "sports", "headline": "Antonelli wins at Spa and opens a commanding 45-point title lead", "summary": "Kimi Antonelli won the Belgian GP ahead of Leclerc and Verstappen; with rival Russell crashing out, his F1 title lead over Hamilton grew to 45 points.", "url": "https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article/antonelli-beats-leclerc-to-belgian-grand-prix-win-to-extend-title-lead-as-russell-retires.MAqSJSgXvRP6dLbwiRbWI", "source_domain": "formula1.com", "tier": "T1", "tags": ["via snippet"], "topics": ["sports"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Kimi Antonelli, the 19-year-old Mercedes driver, won the Belgian Grand Prix by 1.9 seconds from Ferrari's Charles Leclerc, with four-time champion Max Verstappen third — his sixth win in ten races this season. The result that matters, though, was behind him: his nearest challenger and Mercedes team-mate George Russell crashed out on the opening lap after contact with Lewis Hamilton, who took a contested five-second penalty and finished fourth. With Russell scoring nothing, Antonelli now leads the drivers' championship by 45 points over second-placed Hamilton, with Russell a further five points back in third. A weekend that could have tightened the title fight instead blew it open — and left a teenager, rather than the established champions, in clear control.", "why": "F1's next generation isn't coming, it's here: Antonelli is on course to be one of the youngest champions in the sport's history, and with ten races run the veterans are now effectively racing each other for second.", "thread_id": "2026-07-20-sports-antonelli-wins-at-spa-and-opens-a-commanding-45", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-20", "event_date": "2026-07-19", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Kimi Antonelli", "Mercedes", "Charles Leclerc", "George Russell", "Belgian Grand Prix"]}
{"id": "2026-07-20-sports-evenepoel-wins-in-the-alps-but-vingegaard-s-cras", "date": "2026-07-20", "stream": "sports", "headline": "Evenepoel wins in the Alps — but Vingegaard's crash hands the Tour to Pogacar", "summary": "Remco Evenepoel won Tour stage 15 while Jonas Vingegaard abandoned with a broken collarbone, leaving Tadej Pogacar leading the general classification by about five minutes.", "url": "https://www.cyclingnews.com/pro-cycling/teams-riders/jonas-vingegaards-abandon-of-the-tour-de-france-doesnt-just-lengthen-the-already-heavy-odds-of-a-fifth-tadej-pogacar-victory-it-radically-alters-how-well-perceive-it-analysis/", "source_domain": "cyclingnews.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["via snippet"], "topics": ["sports"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "On the Tour's first serious mountain day — Stage 15, Champagnole to the Plateau de Solaison in the Alps — Belgium's Remco Evenepoel outsprinted overall leader Tadej Pogacar for the stage win. But the day turned on a crash: Jonas Vingegaard, the two-time Tour champion and the one rider realistically able to challenge Pogacar, went down roughly 20 km from the finish, broke his collarbone and abandoned the race. That leaves Pogacar leading the general classification (GC — the overall time standings that decide the winner) by about five minutes from Evenepoel, with Isaac del Toro third at 5:58. In effect, the only man who has ever beaten Pogacar at the Tour is out, all but confirming the Slovenian's expected fifth title with the race's final week still to come.", "why": "A three-week Grand Tour is decided as much by who survives as by who is fastest; a collarbone, not a rival's legs, has drained most of the suspense from the finish.", "thread_id": "2026-07-20-sports-evenepoel-wins-in-the-alps-but-vingegaard-s-cras", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-20", "event_date": "2026-07-19", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Tour de France", "Remco Evenepoel", "Jonas Vingegaard", "Tadej Pogacar"]}
{"id": "2026-07-20-sports-staudenmann-wins-the-rigi-schwinget-as-the-swiss", "date": "2026-07-20", "stream": "sports", "headline": "Staudenmann wins the Rigi-Schwinget as the Swiss wrestling season builds", "summary": "Bernese wrestler Fabian Staudenmann beat Lars Zaugg in the final bout to win the Rigi-Schwinget, his second win there after 2024 and his 23rd festival crown.", "url": "https://www.srf.ch/sport/mehr-sport/schwingen/schlussgang-sieg-gegen-zaugg-staudenmann-triumphiert-auf-der-rigi", "source_domain": "srf.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["sports"], "importance": 1, "display_body": "Bernese wrestler Fabian Staudenmann won the Rigi-Schwinget — one of the summer's mountain festivals in Schwingen (Swiss wrestling, contested in a sawdust ring), held on the Rigi above Lake Lucerne — beating fellow Bernese Lars Zaugg in the final bout (Schlussgang) on Sunday. It is his second win on the Rigi after 2024 and his 23rd festival crown. With no Eidgenossisches (the sport's championship, staged only every three years) on the 2026 calendar, individual festival wins like this are how the pecking order among the top wrestlers gets set through late summer.", "why": "For a Swiss reader, Schwingen is a genuine national event, not a niche; Staudenmann is quietly building the form that counts when the biggest festivals arrive.", "thread_id": "2026-07-20-sports-staudenmann-wins-the-rigi-schwinget-as-the-swiss", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-20", "event_date": "2026-07-19", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Fabian Staudenmann", "Lars Zaugg", "Rigi-Schwinget", "Schwingen"]}
